{"title_page": "2008\u201309 FIS Cross-Country World Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox Double Wintersport World Cup\n| title=<!--[[File:F\u00e9d\u00e9ration internationale de ski (logo).svg|28px]]--> 2008\u201309 FIS Cross-Country World Cup\n| competition1=Overall\n| competition1men= {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| competition1ladies= {{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]] \n| competition2=Distance\n| competition2men= {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Pietro Piller Cottrer]]\n| competition2ladies= {{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]]\n| competition3=Sprint\n| competition3men= {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Ola Vigen Hattestad]]\n| competition3ladies= {{flagicon|SLO}} [[Petra Majdi\u010d]] \n| competition4=Nations Cup\n| competition4men= {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Norway]]\n| competition4ladies= {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Finland]]\n| mixedcompetition1=Nations Cup Overall\n| mixedcompetition1both={{flagicon|NOR}} [[Norway]]\n| stageevent1=[[2008\u201309 Tour de Ski|Tour de Ski]]\n| stageevent1men={{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| stageevent1ladies={{flagicon|FIN}} [[Virpi Kuitunen]]\n| stageevent2=World Cup Final\n| stageevent2men={{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| stageevent2ladies={{flagicon|POL}} [[Justyna Kowalczyk]]\n| menlocations=17 venues\n| ladieslocations=17 venues\n| menindividual=30 events\n| ladiesindividual=30 events\n| relaymen=4 events\n| relayladies=4 events\n| cancelledmen=1 event\n| cancelledladies=1 event\n| previous=[[2007\u201308 FIS Cross-Country World Cup|2007\u201308]]\n| next=[[2009\u201310 FIS Cross-Country World Cup|2009\u201310]]\n}}\nThe '''2008\u201309 FIS Cross-Country World Cup''' was a multi-race tournament over the season for cross-country skiers. It was the 28th official [[FIS Cross-Country World Cup|World Cup]] season in [[cross-country skiing (sport)|cross-country skiing]] for men and ladies. The season began on 22 November 2008 with 15&nbsp;km freestyle races for women in [[G\u00e4llivare]], won by [[Charlotte Kalla]] of Sweden. The World Cup is organised by the [[International Ski Federation|FIS]] who also run world cups and championships in [[ski jumping]], [[snowboarding]] and [[alpine skiing]] amongst others.\n\n== Calendar ==\nBoth men's and women's events tend to be held at the same resorts over a 2 or 3 day period. Listed below is a list of races which equates with the points table further down this page.\n\nThe [[Tour de Ski]] is a series of events which count towards the World Cup. This starts with the meet at [[Oberhof, Germany|Oberhof]] and concludes at [[Val di Fiemme]].\n\n===Men===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|+ C \u2013 Classic / F \u2013 Freestyle\n|-\n! Round\n!width=\"120\"| Venue\n!width=\"140\"| Discipline\n!width=\"120\"| Date\n!width=\"200\"| Winner\n!width=\"200\"| Second\n!width=\"200\"| Third\n|-\n! 1\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[G\u00e4llivare]]\n| 15&nbsp;km F\n| 22 November 2008\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Marcus Hellner]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Pietro Piller Cottrer]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n|-\n! 2\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Kuusamo]]\n| Sprint C\n| 29 November 2008\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Ola Vigen Hattestad]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Tor Arne Hetland]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[John Kristian Dahl]]\n|-\n! 3\n| 15&nbsp;km C\n| 30 November 2008\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Martin Johnsrud Sundby]]\n| {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Luk\u00e1\u0161 Bauer]]\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Sami Jauhoj\u00e4rvi]]\n|-\n! 4\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[La Clusaz]]\n| 30&nbsp;km F Mass Start\n| 6 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Alexander Legkov]]\n|-\n! 5\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Davos]]\n| 15&nbsp;km C\n| 13 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Johan Olsson (skier)|Johan Olsson]]\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Axel Teichmann]]\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Sami Jauhoj\u00e4rvi]]\n|-\n! 6\n| Sprint F\n| 14 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Ola Vigen Hattestad]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Johan Kj\u00f8lstad]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Renato Pasini]]\n|-\n! 7\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n| Sprint F\n| 20 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Ola Vigen Hattestad]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Tor Arne Hetland]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Fabio Pasini]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" | \n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6 \n! 8\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{flagicon|GER}} [[Oberhof, Germany|Oberhof]]\n| 3,75&nbsp;km F Prologue\n| 27 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|GER}}  [[Axel Teichmann]]\n| {{flagicon|SUI}}  [[Dario Cologna]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}}  [[Petter Northug]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6  \n! 9\n| 15&nbsp;km C Handicap Start\n| 28 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| {{flagicon|GER}}  [[Axel Teichmann]]\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Devon Kershaw]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6 \n! 10\n| {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Prague]]\n| Sprint F\n| 29 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Tor Arne Hetland]]\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Vasily Rochev (skier, born 1980)|Vasily Rochev]] \n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Jean-Marc Gaillard]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6  \n! 11\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Nov\u00e9 M\u011bsto na Morav\u011b|Nove Mesto]]\n| 15&nbsp;km C\n| 31 December 2008\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Axel Teichmann]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Martin Johnsrud Sundby]]\n| {{flagicon|KAZ}} [[Nikolay Chebotko]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6  \n! 12\n| Sprint F\n| 1 January 2009\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Tor Arne Hetland]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Cristian Zorzi]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6  \n! 13\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Val di Fiemme]]\n| 20&nbsp;km C Mass Start\n| 3 January 2009\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Axel Teichmann]]\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Sami Jauhoj\u00e4rvi]]\n| {{flagicon|KAZ}} [[Nikolay Chebotko]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6  \n! 14\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Val di Fiemme]]\n| 11&nbsp;km F Final Climb\n| 4 January 2009\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Ivan Babikov]]\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Tom Reichelt]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Giorgio Di Centa]]\n|-bgcolor=#BCD4E6 \n|align=\"center\"| '''{{Abbr|TdS|Tour de Ski Overall}}'''\n! colspan=\"3\" | [[2008\u201309 Tour de Ski#Overall Standing|2nd Tour de Ski